data.content:
**Modern MSTest collection assertions** give you clearer failure messages and more readable tests. Here's how to improve your code:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllMeet(users, u => u.IsActive);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | Removed — redundant since `AreEqual(3, ...)` covers it | Less noise |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` | Failure shows *expected vs actual* instead of just "was false" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` | `CollectionAssert.AllMeet(users, ...)` | Reports *which element* failed the predicate |
| `users.Single()` + null check | `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(...))` | `Single` already throws if not found — use `Any` for existence checks |

**Other useful collection assertions:**

- **`CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`** — membership check
- **`CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — same elements, same order
- **`CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)`** — same elements, any order
- **`CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(collection, element)`** — exclusion check

The general rule: **avoid `Assert.IsTrue(boolExpr)`** whenever a more specific assert exists — you get much better diagnostics on failure.
